\hypertarget{section-3-part-1-quadrotor-dynamics-review}{%
\subsection{Section 3: Part 1 --- Quadrotor Dynamics Review}\label{section-3-part-1-quadrotor-dynamics-review}}

You studied quadrotor dynamics extensively in Weeks 3--8 (MATLAB theory block). Here we briefly review the key equations that we will now implement in ROS2 control nodes. The simulation uses the \texttt{quadrotor\_sim.py} physics engine from \texttt{src/ros2\_robotics\_course/week\_06/}, which follows the ENU/FLU convention (x-forward, y-left, z-up) --- the ROS2 standard.

\hypertarget{state-vector}{%
\subsubsection{3.1 State Vector}\label{state-vector}}

The full quadrotor state is a 12-dimensional vector:

\[ \mathbf{x} = \begin{bmatrix} x & y & z & \phi & \theta & \psi & \dot{x} & \dot{y} & \dot{z} & p & q & r \end{bmatrix}^T \]

where \((x, y, z)\) is the position in the world ENU frame, \((\phi, \theta, \psi)\) are roll, pitch, yaw (ZYX Euler angles), \((\dot{x}, \dot{y}, \dot{z})\) are world-frame velocities, and \((p, q, r)\) are body-frame angular rates.

\hypertarget{translational-dynamics}{%
\subsubsection{3.2 Translational Dynamics}\label{translational-dynamics}}

Applying Newton\textquotesingle s second law in the world frame:

\[ m\ddot{\mathbf{p}} = \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ -mg \end{bmatrix} + R(\phi,\theta,\psi) \begin{bmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \\ T \end{bmatrix} \]

where \(m\) is the total mass, \(g = 9.81\;\text{m/s}^2\), \(T\) is the total thrust along the body z-axis, and \(R(\phi,\theta,\psi)\) is the ZYX rotation matrix (body-to-world):

\[ R = R_z(\psi) R_y(\theta) R_x(\phi) = \begin{bmatrix} c\theta c\psi & c\psi s\theta s\phi - s\psi c\phi & c\psi s\theta c\phi + s\psi s\phi \\ c\theta s\psi & s\psi s\theta s\phi + c\psi c\phi & s\psi s\theta c\phi - c\psi s\phi \\ -s\theta & c\theta s\phi & c\theta c\phi \end{bmatrix} \]

\hypertarget{rotational-dynamics}{%
\subsubsection{3.3 Rotational Dynamics}\label{rotational-dynamics}}

Euler\textquotesingle s equation for rotational motion in the body frame:

\[ J\dot{\boldsymbol{\omega}} = -\boldsymbol{\omega} \times J\boldsymbol{\omega} + \boldsymbol{\tau} \]

where \(J = \text{diag}(I_{xx}, I_{yy}, I_{zz})\) is the inertia tensor (diagonal for a symmetric quadrotor), \(\boldsymbol{\omega} = [p, q, r]^T\) are body angular rates, and \(\boldsymbol{\tau} = [\tau_\phi, \tau_\theta, \tau_\psi]^T\) are the control torques.

Expanding component-wise:

\[ \begin{aligned}
                I_{xx}\dot{p} &= (I_{yy} - I_{zz})qr + \tau_\phi \\
                I_{yy}\dot{q} &= (I_{zz} - I_{xx})pr + \tau_\theta \\
                I_{zz}\dot{r} &= (I_{xx} - I_{yy})pq + \tau_\psi
                \end{aligned} \]

\hypertarget{motor-mixing-matrix}{%
\subsubsection{3.4 Motor Mixing Matrix}\label{motor-mixing-matrix}}

The four motors (plus-configuration) produce a total thrust \(T\) and three torques \((\tau_\phi, \tau_\theta, \tau_\psi)\). The relationship is:

\[ \begin{bmatrix} T \\ \tau_\phi \\ \tau_\theta \\ \tau_\psi \end{bmatrix} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} k_f & k_f & k_f & k_f \\ 0 & -dk_f & 0 & dk_f \\ dk_f & 0 & -dk_f & 0 \\ -k_m & k_m & -k_m & k_m \end{bmatrix}}_{\displaystyle M} \begin{bmatrix} \omega_1^2 \\ \omega_2^2 \\ \omega_3^2 \\ \omega_4^2 \end{bmatrix} \]

where \(k_f\) is the thrust coefficient, \(k_m\) is the torque coefficient, \(d\) is the arm length, and \(\omega_i\) is the angular speed of motor \(i\). The inverse mixing matrix \(M^{-1}\) converts desired thrust/torques to motor speed commands:

\[ \begin{bmatrix} \omega_1^2 \\ \omega_2^2 \\ \omega_3^2 \\ \omega_4^2 \end{bmatrix} = M^{-1} \begin{bmatrix} T \\ \tau_\phi \\ \tau_\theta \\ \tau_\psi \end{bmatrix} \]

\textbf{Physical Parameters (from quadrotor\_sim.py):} mass = 1.0 kg, arm\_length = 0.25 m, \(I_{xx} = I_{yy} = 0.0082\;\text{kg}\cdot\text{m}^2\), \(I_{zz} = 0.0150\;\text{kg}\cdot\text{m}^2\), \(k_f = 6.8 \times 10^{-6}\), \(k_m = 2.6 \times 10^{-7}\), motor range: 0--838 rad/s.

\hypertarget{quadrotor-plus-configuration-diagram}{%
\subsubsection{3.5 Quadrotor Plus-Configuration Diagram}\label{quadrotor-plus-configuration-diagram}}

The following diagram shows the motor layout, rotation directions, thrust vectors, and body-frame axes for a plus-configuration quadrotor:

\hypertarget{section-4-part-2-cascaded-control-architecture-in-ros2}{%
\subsection{Section 4: Part 2 --- Cascaded Control Architecture in ROS2}\label{section-4-part-2-cascaded-control-architecture-in-ros2}}

The standard control architecture used by virtually all commercial and research flight controllers (DJI, PX4, ArduPilot, BetaFlight) is a \textbf{cascaded loop} structure. Each loop operates at a different frequency, with inner loops running faster than outer loops.

\hypertarget{three-loop-cascade}{%
\subsubsection{4.1 Three-Loop Cascade}\label{three-loop-cascade}}

\hypertarget{outer-loop-position-controller}{%
\paragraph{Outer Loop: Position Controller}\label{outer-loop-position-controller}}

\textbf{Rate:} 10--50 Hz

\textbf{Input:} Desired position \((x_d, y_d, z_d)\) from mission planner

\textbf{Output:} Desired attitude angles \((\phi_d, \theta_d)\) and thrust \(T_d\)

\textbf{Sensor:} GPS/vision (position), barometer (altitude)

This loop converts position error into desired accelerations, then maps accelerations to desired tilt angles using the small-angle approximation.

\hypertarget{middle-loop-attitude-controller}{%
\paragraph{Middle Loop: Attitude Controller}\label{middle-loop-attitude-controller}}

\textbf{Rate:} 100--250 Hz

\textbf{Input:} Desired attitude \((\phi_d, \theta_d, \psi_d)\)

\textbf{Output:} Desired angular rates \((p_d, q_d, r_d)\)

\textbf{Sensor:} IMU (accelerometer-derived attitude via complementary or Mahony filter)

Proportional control on attitude error to generate rate setpoints. This decouples attitude from rate dynamics.

\hypertarget{inner-loop-rate-controller}{%
\paragraph{Inner Loop: Rate Controller}\label{inner-loop-rate-controller}}

\textbf{Rate:} 250--1000 Hz

\textbf{Input:} Desired angular rates \((p_d, q_d, r_d)\)

\textbf{Output:} Motor commands (PWM or speed)

\textbf{Sensor:} Gyroscope (direct angular rate measurement, no filtering needed)

Full PID on rate error. This is the tightest loop and must run fastest for stability.

\textbf{Why Cascaded?} A single loop from position to motors would need to invert the full nonlinear dynamics at every step, requiring extremely high bandwidth. By cascading, each loop only needs to stabilize one dynamic mode: the inner rate loop damps oscillations, the attitude loop tracks orientation, and the outer loop tracks position. Each loop sees the next inner loop as an approximately instantaneous actuator (because the inner loop is 5--10x faster).

\hypertarget{cascaded-architecture-block-diagram}{%
\subsubsection{4.2 Cascaded Architecture Block Diagram}\label{cascaded-architecture-block-diagram}}

\hypertarget{ros2-topic-structure}{%
\subsubsection{4.3 ROS2 Topic Structure}\label{ros2-topic-structure}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lllll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Topic Name & Message Type & Publisher & Subscriber(s) & Rate (Hz) \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\texttt{/position\_ref} & geometry\_msgs/Point & Mission Planner & /position\_controller & 10 \\
\texttt{/attitude\_cmd} & geometry\_msgs/Vector3 & /position\_controller & /attitude\_controller & 50 \\
\texttt{/rate\_cmd} & geometry\_msgs/Vector3 & /attitude\_controller & /rate\_controller & 250 \\
\texttt{/motor\_cmd} & std\_msgs/Float64MultiArray & /rate\_controller & /motor\_mixer & 250 \\
\texttt{/motor\_speeds} & std\_msgs/Float64MultiArray & /motor\_mixer & /quadrotor\_sim & 250 \\
\texttt{/odom} & nav\_msgs/Odometry & /quadrotor\_sim & /position\_controller & 50 \\
\texttt{/imu} & sensor\_msgs/Imu & /quadrotor\_sim & /attitude\_controller, /rate\_controller & 250 \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{launch-file-for-cascaded-system}{%
\subsubsection{4.4 Launch File for Cascaded System}\label{launch-file-for-cascaded-system}}

{from} launch {import} LaunchDescription
{from} launch\_ros.actions {import} Node
{def} {generate\_launch\_description}():
{return} LaunchDescription({[}
{\# Quadrotor physics simulation}
Node(
package={\textquotesingle quadrotor\_control\textquotesingle{}},
executable={\textquotesingle quadrotor\_sim\_node\textquotesingle{}},
name={\textquotesingle quadrotor\_sim\textquotesingle{}},
parameters={[}\{{\textquotesingle dt\textquotesingle{}}: 0.001, {\textquotesingle mass\textquotesingle{}}: 1.0\}{]},
),
{\# Position controller (outer loop, 50 Hz)}
Node(
package={\textquotesingle quadrotor\_control\textquotesingle{}},
executable={\textquotesingle position\_controller\_node\textquotesingle{}},
name={\textquotesingle position\_controller\textquotesingle{}},
parameters={[}\{{\textquotesingle rate\textquotesingle{}}: 50.0, {\textquotesingle kp\_xy\textquotesingle{}}: 1.5, {\textquotesingle kd\_xy\textquotesingle{}}: 1.0\}{]},
),
{\# Attitude controller (middle loop, 250 Hz)}
Node(
package={\textquotesingle quadrotor\_control\textquotesingle{}},
