),
{]})

\hypertarget{section-5-part-3-implementing-pid-attitude-controller-in-ros2}{%
\subsection{Section 5: Part 3 --- Implementing PID Attitude Controller in ROS2}\label{section-5-part-3-implementing-pid-attitude-controller-in-ros2}}

Below is a complete ROS2 Python node implementing a cascaded PID attitude controller. It subscribes to \texttt{/imu} for current attitude and \texttt{/attitude\_cmd} for desired orientation, then publishes torque/thrust commands on \texttt{/motor\_cmd}.

\hypertarget{full-pid-attitude-controller-node}{%
\subsubsection{5.1 Full PID Attitude Controller Node}\label{full-pid-attitude-controller-node}}

{\#!/usr/bin/env python3}
{"""PID Attitude Controller - ROS2 Node for Quadrotor."""}
{import} rclpy
{from} rclpy.node {import} Node
{from} sensor\_msgs.msg {import} Imu
{from} geometry\_msgs.msg {import} Vector3
{from} std\_msgs.msg {import} Float64MultiArray
{import} numpy {as} np
{from} math {import} atan2, asin, sqrt
{class} {PIDAttitudeController}(Node):
{def} {\_\_init\_\_}(self):
{super}().\_\_init\_\_({\textquotesingle pid\_attitude\_controller\textquotesingle{}})
{\# PID gains: {[}roll, pitch, yaw{]}}
self.kp = np.array({[}6.0, 6.0, 3.0{]})
self.ki = np.array({[}0.5, 0.5, 0.2{]})
self.kd = np.array({[}2.0, 2.0, 1.0{]})
self.integral = np.zeros(3)
self.prev\_error = np.zeros(3)
self.integral\_limit = 2.0
self.des\_rpy = np.zeros(3) {\# desired roll, pitch, yaw}
self.cur\_rpy = np.zeros(3) {\# current roll, pitch, yaw}
self.cur\_rates = np.zeros(3) {\# current angular rates}
{\# Complementary filter state}
self.alpha = 0.98
self.cf\_rpy = np.zeros(3)
self.cf\_init = {False}
{\# Subscribers}
self.create\_subscription(Imu, {\textquotesingle/imu\textquotesingle{}}, self.imu\_cb, 10)
self.create\_subscription(Vector3, {\textquotesingle/attitude\_cmd\textquotesingle{}}, self.cmd\_cb, 10)
{\# Publisher}
self.cmd\_pub = self.create\_publisher(Float64MultiArray, {\textquotesingle/motor\_cmd\textquotesingle{}}, 10)
{\# Timer at 250 Hz}
self.dt = 1.0 / 250.0
self.create\_timer(self.dt, self.control\_loop)
self.get\_logger().info({\textquotesingle PID Attitude Controller started at 250 Hz\textquotesingle{}})
{def} {quat\_to\_euler}(self, q):
{"""Convert quaternion (x,y,z,w) to Euler (roll, pitch, yaw)."""}
x, y, z, w = q.x, q.y, q.z, q.w
sinr = 2.0 * (w * x + y * z)
cosr = 1.0 - 2.0 * (x * x + y * y)
roll = atan2(sinr, cosr)
sinp = 2.0 * (w * y - z * x)
pitch = asin(max(-1.0, min(1.0, sinp)))
siny = 2.0 * (w * z + x * y)
cosy = 1.0 - 2.0 * (y * y + z * z)
yaw = atan2(siny, cosy)
{return} np.array({[}roll, pitch, yaw{]})
{def} {imu\_cb}(self, msg):
{"""Process IMU: complementary filter for attitude."""}
accel\_rpy = self.quat\_to\_euler(msg.orientation)
gyro = np.array({[}msg.angular\_velocity.x,
msg.angular\_velocity.y,
msg.angular\_velocity.z{]})
self.cur\_rates = gyro
{if not} self.cf\_init:
self.cf\_rpy = accel\_rpy
self.cf\_init = {True}
{else}:
self.cf\_rpy = (self.alpha * (self.cf\_rpy + gyro * self.dt)
+ (1 - self.alpha) * accel\_rpy)
self.cur\_rpy = self.cf\_rpy
{def} {cmd\_cb}(self, msg):
self.des\_rpy = np.array({[}msg.x, msg.y, msg.z{]})
{def} {control\_loop}(self):
error = self.des\_rpy - self.cur\_rpy
self.integral += error * self.dt
self.integral = np.clip(self.integral, -self.integral\_limit,
self.integral\_limit)
derivative = -self.cur\_rates {\# use gyro directly}
torque = (self.kp * error + self.ki * self.integral
+ self.kd * derivative)
msg = Float64MultiArray()
msg.data = torque.tolist()
self.cmd\_pub.publish(msg)
{def} {main}():
rclpy.init()
rclpy.spin(PIDAttitudeController())
rclpy.shutdown()
{if} \_\_name\_\_ == {\textquotesingle\_\_main\_\_\textquotesingle{}}:
main()

\hypertarget{complementary-filter-for-attitude-estimation}{%
\subsubsection{5.2 Complementary Filter for Attitude Estimation}\label{complementary-filter-for-attitude-estimation}}

The complementary filter fuses gyroscope integration (high-frequency, drift-prone) with accelerometer-derived angles (low-frequency, noisy) to produce a stable attitude estimate:

\[ \hat{\phi}_{k+1} = \alpha\bigl(\hat{\phi}_k + \omega_x \,\Delta t\bigr) + (1 - \alpha)\,\phi_\text{acc} \]

where:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \(\alpha \in [0.95, 0.99]\) is the filter coefficient (higher = more trust in gyroscope)
\item
  \(\omega_x\) is the gyroscope angular rate about the x-axis
\item
  \(\phi_\text{acc} = \text{atan2}(a_y, a_z)\) is the accelerometer-derived roll angle
\item
  \(\Delta t\) is the time step between IMU samples
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Why not just use the gyroscope?} Gyroscope integration drifts over time due to bias. The accelerometer provides an absolute reference (gravity direction) but is noisy and affected by translational acceleration. The complementary filter combines the best of both: short-term accuracy from the gyro and long-term stability from the accelerometer. For production systems, a Mahony or Madgwick filter (quaternion-based) is preferred.

The same principle applies for pitch:

\[ \hat{\theta}_{k+1} = \alpha\bigl(\hat{\theta}_k + \omega_y \,\Delta t\bigr) + (1 - \alpha)\,\theta_\text{acc} \]

where \(\theta_\text{acc} = \text{atan2}\bigl(-a_x,\;\sqrt{a_y^2 + a_z^2}\bigr)\). Yaw cannot be corrected by the accelerometer alone --- it requires a magnetometer or visual heading.

\hypertarget{section-6-part-4-applying-all-7-controllers-to-quadrotor}{%
\subsection{Section 6: Part 4 --- Applying All 7 Controllers to Quadrotor}\label{section-6-part-4-applying-all-7-controllers-to-quadrotor}}

In Weeks 1--8 you studied seven control strategies in the abstract. In Week 9 you implemented them as generic ROS2 nodes. Now we map each controller specifically to the quadrotor dynamics and discuss the practical ROS2 implementation considerations.

\hypertarget{computed-torque-control-ctc}{%
\subsubsection{6.1 Computed Torque Control (CTC)}\label{computed-torque-control-ctc}}

\hypertarget{concept}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept}}

Computed Torque Control (also called \emph{feedback linearization}) cancels the nonlinear terms in the rotational dynamics and replaces them with a desired linear response:

\[ \boldsymbol{\tau} = J\mathbf{u}_d + \boldsymbol{\omega} \times J\boldsymbol{\omega} \]

where \(\mathbf{u}_d = \ddot{\mathbf{q}}_d + K_d(\dot{\mathbf{q}}_d - \dot{\mathbf{q}}) + K_p(\mathbf{q}_d - \mathbf{q})\) is the auxiliary PD input. After cancellation, the closed-loop system reduces to \(\ddot{\mathbf{e}} + K_d\dot{\mathbf{e}} + K_p\mathbf{e} = 0\), which is a linear second-order system with tunable damping.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Requires:} Accurate inertia matrix \(J\). Sensitive to payload changes.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} The Coriolis/gyroscopic term \(\boldsymbol{\omega} \times J\boldsymbol{\omega}\) is computed in each timer callback using the latest gyroscope reading. Publishes torque commands.
\item
  \textbf{Best for:} Known, well-characterized platforms where the model is accurate.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{model-predictive-control-mpc}{%
\subsubsection{6.2 Model Predictive Control (MPC)}\label{model-predictive-control-mpc}}

\hypertarget{concept-1}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-1}}

Linearize the quadrotor dynamics about the hover operating point. At each control cycle, solve a finite-horizon constrained optimization:

\[ \min_{\mathbf{u}_{0:N-1}} \sum_{k=0}^{N-1} \bigl(\|\mathbf{x}_k - \mathbf{x}_\text{ref}\|_Q^2 + \|\mathbf{u}_k\|_R^2\bigr) + \|\mathbf{x}_N - \mathbf{x}_\text{ref}\|_P^2 \]

subject to \(\mathbf{x}_{k+1} = A\mathbf{x}_k + B\mathbf{u}_k\), thrust limits \(0 \le T \le T_\text{max}\), and angle constraints \(|\phi| \le 30^\circ, |\theta| \le 30^\circ\).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Handles:} Thrust saturation and angle limits explicitly. Can preview reference trajectories.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} Heavier computation; run at 10--20 Hz in a separate thread or as the outer position loop. Use OSQP or acados for the QP solver. Apply only the first control action.
\item
  \textbf{Industry:} ETH Zurich (aggressive aerobatics), Skydio (obstacle avoidance), DJI Matrice (waypoint tracking).
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{adaptive-control}{%
\subsubsection{6.3 Adaptive Control}\label{adaptive-control}}

\hypertarget{concept-2}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-2}}

Online estimation of uncertain parameters (mass \(m\), inertia \(J\), aerodynamic coefficients) using the regressor form:

\[ \boldsymbol{\tau} = Y(\mathbf{q}, \dot{\mathbf{q}}, \dot{\mathbf{q}}_r, \ddot{\mathbf{q}}_r)\,\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}} + K_d\mathbf{s} \]

where \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\) is the parameter estimate vector, \(Y\) is the regressor matrix, and \(\mathbf{s} = \dot{\mathbf{e}} + \Lambda\mathbf{e}\) is the sliding variable. The update law is \(\dot{\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}} = -\Gamma^{-1}Y^T\mathbf{s}\).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Use case:} Quadrotor picking up unknown payloads (mass changes mid-flight), battery depletion changing mass.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} Parameter update runs alongside the control law in the same callback. Store \(\hat{\boldsymbol{\theta}}\) as node state. Publish parameter estimates for monitoring on \texttt{/param\_estimates}.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{robust-control-h-infinity-sliding-boundary-layer}{%
\subsubsection{6.4 Robust Control (H-infinity / Sliding Boundary Layer)}\label{robust-control-h-infinity-sliding-boundary-layer}}

\hypertarget{concept-3}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-3}}

Add a robust compensating term to handle bounded disturbances (wind, ground effect, model uncertainty):

\[ \boldsymbol{\tau} = \boldsymbol{\tau}_\text{nominal} + \boldsymbol{\tau}_\text{robust} \]

where \(\boldsymbol{\tau}_\text{robust} = -\rho\,\text{sgn}(\mathbf{s})\) with \(\rho \geq \|\mathbf{d}\|_\infty\). To avoid chattering, a boundary layer is used: \(\text{sat}(\mathbf{s}/\epsilon)\) replaces \(\text{sgn}(\mathbf{s})\).

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Use case:} Outdoor flight with wind gusts up to 10 m/s, flying near structures (ground effect).
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} A wind estimator node subscribes to \texttt{/imu} and \texttt{/odom}, estimates disturbance force, and publishes on \texttt{/wind\_estimate}. The robust compensator node uses this estimate to set the disturbance bound \(\rho\).
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{backstepping-control}{%
\subsubsection{6.5 Backstepping Control}\label{backstepping-control}}

\hypertarget{concept-4}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-4}}

Backstepping is a natural fit for the cascaded quadrotor structure. Design proceeds in two steps:

\[ \begin{aligned}
                    \text{Step 1 (outer):}\quad &\text{Position error} \;\rightarrow\; \text{Virtual control: desired attitude } (\phi_d, \theta_d, T_d) \\
                    \text{Step 2 (inner):}\quad &\text{Attitude error} \;\rightarrow\; \text{Actual torques } \boldsymbol{\tau}
                    \end{aligned} \]

Each step uses a Lyapunov function to prove stability. The virtual control from Step 1 becomes the reference for Step 2.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Advantage:} Formal stability guarantee via Lyapunov analysis. Handles the underactuated nature (4 inputs, 6 DOF) naturally through the virtual control.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} Two-node architecture mirrors the two backstepping steps: \texttt{/backstepping\_outer} (position) and \texttt{/backstepping\_inner} (attitude). The outer node publishes desired attitude for the inner node.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{sliding-mode-control-smc}{%
\subsubsection{6.6 Sliding Mode Control (SMC)}\label{sliding-mode-control-smc}}

\hypertarget{concept-5}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-5}}

Define a sliding surface for each attitude axis:

\[ s_\phi = \dot{e}_\phi + \lambda_\phi\, e_\phi \]

The control law drives the state to the surface and maintains it there:

\[ \tau_\phi = I_{xx}\bigl(\ddot{\phi}_d + \lambda_\phi\,\dot{e}_\phi - \eta\,\text{sat}(s_\phi / \epsilon)\bigr) - (I_{yy} - I_{zz})qr \]

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Strength:} Excellent disturbance rejection for matched disturbances (wind acting through control channels). Invariant to parameter uncertainty once on the surface.
\item
  \textbf{Chattering:} Mitigated with boundary layer \(\epsilon\) or super-twisting algorithm.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Implementation:} Requires a fast inner loop (500--1000 Hz) to maintain sliding condition. Timer period = 1--2 ms. Use \texttt{BEST\_EFFORT} QoS to avoid blocking.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{nonlinear-control-optimization-ilqr-nmpc-week-8}{%
\subsubsection{6.7 Nonlinear Control Optimization --- iLQR / NMPC (Week 8)}\label{nonlinear-control-optimization-ilqr-nmpc-week-8}}

\hypertarget{concept-6}{%
\paragraph{Concept}\label{concept-6}}

Rather than linearising the quadrotor around hover once, \textbf{iLQR} (Week 8 §9) linearises around the \emph{current-iterate trajectory} at every iteration and solves a time-varying LQR in closed form. The discrete-time recursion computes, for \(k = N\!-\!1,\ldots,0\):

\[ k_k = -Q_{uu,k}^{-1} Q_{u,k},\quad K_k = -Q_{uu,k}^{-1} Q_{ux,k} \]
\[ u_k^{\text{new}} = \bar u_k + \alpha\,k_k + K_k\,(x_k - \bar x_k) \]

where \(Q_{uu}, Q_{ux}, Q_u\) are Jacobian/Hessian blocks assembled from the nonlinear dynamics \(f\) and cost \(L\) (see Week 8 §9 notation table). Wrapped in a receding-horizon loop this is \textbf{NMPC}.

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Advantage:} Handles the full nonlinear quadrotor model including tilt saturation and aggressive manoeuvres where linearised LQR fails; simultaneously provides an open-loop plan \emph{and} a local time-varying feedback policy \(K_k\).
\item
  \textbf{Limitation:} Iterative, higher compute per step than LQR; locally (not globally) optimal; needs warm-starting across samples to meet real-time.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 implementation:} Timer callback at 50--100 Hz runs 3--5 iLQR iterations with warm-started control sequence; finite-difference Jacobians for the 6- or 12-state quadrotor; apply \(u_0^\star\), shift the warm-start. See \texttt{week\_09/w11\_exercises/task\_nmpc\_node.py} for the unicycle template.
\item
  \textbf{Meta-use:} iLQR/NMPC is also the offline tuning tool for the other six controllers --- minimising a closed-loop cost \(J(\theta)\) over SMC gains \((\lambda,\phi,\eta)\), adaptive \((\Gamma,\sigma)\), robust \((K_p,K_d,\rho,\Lambda)\), or backstepping \((k_1,\ldots,k_n)\) as shown in Week 8 §5--§8.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{comprehensive-controller-comparison}{%
\subsubsection{6.8 Comprehensive Controller Comparison}\label{comprehensive-controller-comparison}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lllllll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Controller & Hover RMSE (cm) & Trajectory RMSE (cm) & Wind Rejection (3 m/s) & Computation / Cycle & Tuning Params & Industry Example \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\textbf{PID} & 3.2 & 8.5 & Moderate (15 cm drift) & \textless1 μs & 9 (Kp, Ki, Kd × 3 axes) & ArduPilot, BetaFlight \\
\textbf{CTC} & 2.1 & 5.8 & Poor (model mismatch) & \textasciitilde5 μs & 6 (Kp, Kd × 3) + model & Research platforms \\
\textbf{MPC} & 1.8 & 3.2 & Good (12 cm drift) & 1--50 ms & Q, R matrices + N horizon & Skydio, ETH Zurich \\
\textbf{Adaptive} & 2.5 & 6.1 & Good (adapts to steady wind) & \textasciitilde20 μs & Γ, Λ + regressor structure & Payload-carrying drones \\
\textbf{Robust} & 2.8 & 7.0 & Excellent (5 cm drift) & \textasciitilde10 μs & ρ, ε + nominal gains & Military / outdoor UAVs \\
\textbf{Backstepping} & 2.0 & 4.5 & Good (10 cm drift) & \textasciitilde15 μs & k\textsubscript{1}--k\textsubscript{6} (Lyapunov gains) & Academic, Parrot AR.Drone \\
\textbf{SMC} & 2.4 & 5.5 & Excellent (4 cm drift) & \textasciitilde8 μs & λ, η, ε per axis & DJI (inner loop elements) \\
\textbf{LQR} & 1.5 & 6.8 & Moderate (14 cm drift) & \textasciitilde2 μs & Q, R diagonal entries & PX4 (mc\_pos\_control) \\
\end{longtable}

\textbf{Key Insight:} No single controller dominates across all metrics. PID is the industry standard due to simplicity and robustness of tuning. MPC excels at trajectory tracking with constraints. SMC and Robust control are superior for wind rejection. LQR is optimal for hover energy efficiency. In practice, many production systems blend approaches --- for example, PX4 uses a cascaded PID structure but the position loop effectively implements LQR-like gains computed from a simplified model.

\hypertarget{section-7-part-5-quadrotor-simulation-in-ros2}{%
\subsection{Section 7: Part 5 --- Quadrotor Simulation in ROS2}\label{section-7-part-5-quadrotor-simulation-in-ros2}}

\hypertarget{simulation-environment}{%
\subsubsection{7.1 Simulation Environment}\label{simulation-environment}}

The simulation uses the \texttt{quadrotor\_sim.py} physics engine from the ROS2 Robotics Course (Week 6). Key features:

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Physics Engine:} 12-state rigid-body dynamics with RK4 integration at 1 kHz internal rate
\item
  \textbf{Convention:} ENU/FLU (x-forward, y-left, z-up) --- ROS2 standard
\item
  \textbf{Motor Model:} First-order motor dynamics with thrust coefficient \(k_f = 6.8 \times 10^{-6}\) and torque coefficient \(k_m = 2.6 \times 10^{-7}\)
\item
  \textbf{Sensor Models:} IMU with configurable noise (gyro bias, accelerometer noise), GPS with position noise
\item
  \textbf{Motor Layout:} Plus-configuration with M1 (front, CW), M2 (left, CCW), M3 (rear, CW), M4 (right, CCW)
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{ros2-integration}{%
\subsubsection{7.2 ROS2 Integration}\label{ros2-integration}}

The simulation node publishes sensor data and subscribes to motor commands:

{\# quadrotor\_sim\_node.py - Wraps quadrotor\_sim.py as a ROS2 node}
{class} {QuadrotorSimNode}(Node):
{def} {\_\_init\_\_}(self):
{super}().\_\_init\_\_({\textquotesingle quadrotor\_sim\textquotesingle{}})
{\# Publishers: sensor data}
self.odom\_pub = self.create\_publisher(Odometry, {\textquotesingle/odom\textquotesingle{}}, 10)
self.imu\_pub = self.create\_publisher(Imu, {\textquotesingle/imu\textquotesingle{}}, 10)
{\# Subscriber: motor commands}
self.create\_subscription(Float64MultiArray,
{\textquotesingle/motor\_speeds\textquotesingle{}}, self.motor\_cb, 10)
{\# TF broadcaster for RViz2}
self.tf\_broadcaster = TransformBroadcaster(self)
{\# Simulation state}
self.state = np.zeros(12)
self.state{[}2{]} = 0.0 {\# start on ground}
self.params = QuadrotorParams()
self.create\_timer(0.001, self.step\_sim) {\# 1 kHz physics}

\hypertarget{visualization-in-rviz2}{%
\subsubsection{7.3 Visualization in RViz2}\label{visualization-in-rviz2}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{TF Frames:} Broadcast \texttt{world} → \texttt{base\_link} transform at 100 Hz. Attach \texttt{rotor\_1}--\texttt{rotor\_4} child frames for motor visualization.
\item
  \textbf{Markers:} Use \texttt{visualization\_msgs/MarkerArray} to render the quadrotor body (cube for center mass, cylinders for arms, rotating discs for propellers).
\item
  \textbf{Trajectory:} Publish \texttt{nav\_msgs/Path} on \texttt{/trajectory} to show the flight path as a line strip in RViz2.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{recording-flight-data-with-rosbag2}{%
\subsubsection{7.4 Recording Flight Data with rosbag2}\label{recording-flight-data-with-rosbag2}}

{\# Record all relevant topics during a flight test}
ros2 bag record /odom /imu /attitude\_cmd /rate\_cmd /motor\_cmd /motor\_speeds \textbackslash{}
-o flight\_test\_pid\_hover
{\# Replay for post-flight analysis}
ros2 bag play flight\_test\_pid\_hover
{\# Convert to CSV for MATLAB/Python plotting}
ros2 bag convert -i flight\_test\_pid\_hover -o flight\_data.csv

\hypertarget{lab-exercises-from-ros2-robotics-course-week-6}{%
\subsubsection{7.5 Lab Exercises from ROS2 Robotics Course (Week 6)}\label{lab-exercises-from-ros2-robotics-course-week-6}}

The following lab exercises from \texttt{src/ros2\_robotics\_course/week\_06/lab\_exercises/} build up to a complete quadrotor simulation. This week, you will use these as your foundation and swap in different controllers:

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Task & File & Description \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Task 1 & \texttt{task1\_rotation\_math.py} & Rotation mathematics: Euler angles to rotation matrix, quaternion operations, conversions between representations \\
Task 2 & \texttt{task2\_dynamics\_model.py} & Implement the 12-state quadrotor dynamics model, compute state derivatives, RK4 integration \\
Task 3 & \texttt{task3\_pid\_attitude.py} & Cascaded PID attitude controller with outer angle loop and inner rate loop \\
Task 4 & \texttt{task4\_motor\_mixing.py} & Motor mixing matrix construction and inversion, mapping from thrust/torques to motor speeds \\
Task 5 & \texttt{task5\_cascaded\_control.py} & Full cascaded position + attitude control: position PD → desired acceleration → desired attitude → PID → motors \\
Task 6 & \texttt{task6\_complementary\_filter.py} & Complementary filter implementation fusing gyroscope and accelerometer data \\
Task 7 & \texttt{task7\_full\_simulation.py} & Full simulation: fly a square trajectory with cascaded controller, 4-panel visualization \\
\end{longtable}

\textbf{Integration with This Week:} Tasks 1--4 provide the foundation (dynamics, mixing, PID). Task 5 gives the cascaded structure. Your job this week is to replace the inner PID controller in Task 5 with each of the seven controllers (CTC, MPC, Adaptive, Robust, Backstepping, SMC, LQR) and compare performance on the same trajectory.

\hypertarget{section-8-hands-on-activities}{%
\subsection{Section 8: Hands-On Activities}\label{section-8-hands-on-activities}}

\hypertarget{activity-1-pid-hover-test}{%
\subsubsection{Activity 1: PID Hover Test}\label{activity-1-pid-hover-test}}

\textbf{Objective:} Implement the PID attitude controller from Section 5 as a ROS2 node and verify stable hover.

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Create a ROS2 package \texttt{quadrotor\_control} with the PID attitude controller node.
\item
  Configure the cascaded system: position controller (outer), PID attitude controller (inner), motor mixer.
\item
  Set the hover reference to \([x, y, z] = [0, 0, 1]\) m.
\item
  Run the simulation for 30 seconds and record the flight with rosbag2.
\item
  Plot the attitude angles \((\phi, \theta, \psi)\) versus time. Verify:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Settling time \textless{} 2 seconds
  \item
    Steady-state attitude error \textless{} 0.5 degrees
  \item
    Position RMSE \textless{} 5 cm during hover
  \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

{\# Terminal 1: Launch simulation + controllers}
ros2 launch quadrotor\_control cascaded\_hover.launch.py
{\# Terminal 2: Record data}
ros2 bag record /odom /imu /attitude\_cmd /motor\_cmd -o hover\_test\_pid
{\# Terminal 3: Monitor in real-time}
ros2 topic echo /odom -\/-field pose.pose.position

\hypertarget{activity-2-trajectory-tracking-pid-vs-lqr-vs-mpc}{%
\subsubsection{Activity 2: Trajectory Tracking --- PID vs LQR vs MPC}\label{activity-2-trajectory-tracking-pid-vs-lqr-vs-mpc}}

\textbf{Objective:} Fly a square trajectory and compare three controllers quantitatively.

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Define the square trajectory waypoints at 1 m altitude:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    \([0, 0, 1] \rightarrow [2, 0, 1] \rightarrow [2, 2, 1] \rightarrow [0, 2, 1] \rightarrow [0, 0, 1]\)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Implement the LQR controller node:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Linearize around hover, solve CARE using \texttt{scipy.linalg.solve\_continuous\_are}
  \item
    Precompute gain matrix \(K\), apply \(\mathbf{u} = -K(\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{x}_d)\) in callback
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Implement the MPC controller node:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Use OSQP solver with prediction horizon \(N = 20\) at 20 Hz
  \item
    Thrust constraint: \(0 \le T \le 2mg\); angle constraint: \(|\phi|, |\theta| \le 30^\circ\)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Run each controller on the same trajectory. Record rosbag for each run.
\item
  Generate comparison plots:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    3D trajectory overlay (PID = blue, LQR = green, MPC = red)
  \item
    Position tracking error vs time for each axis
  \item
    RMSE table: compute position RMSE for each controller
  \item
    Motor effort: plot total motor speed squared (energy proxy) vs time
  \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{activity-3-wind-disturbance-rejection-smc-vs-robust-vs-pid}{%
\subsubsection{Activity 3: Wind Disturbance Rejection --- SMC vs Robust vs PID}\label{activity-3-wind-disturbance-rejection-smc-vs-robust-vs-pid}}

\textbf{Objective:} Add a simulated constant wind disturbance and compare rejection performance.

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Modify \texttt{quadrotor\_sim\_node.py} to add a constant external force:

  {\# In quadrotor\_dynamics(), add wind force (3 m/s in x)}
  wind\_speed = 3.0 {\# m/s in world x-direction}
  drag\_coeff = 0.1 {\# N/(m/s)}
  F\_wind = np.array({[}drag\_coeff * wind\_speed, 0.0, 0.0{]})
  acc += F\_wind / m {\# add to translational acceleration}
\item
  Implement SMC attitude controller:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Sliding surface: \(s = \dot{e} + \lambda e\) with \(\lambda = 5\)
  \item
    Reaching law: \(\tau = \tau_\text{eq} + \eta \cdot \text{sat}(s/\epsilon)\) with \(\eta = 2.0\), \(\epsilon = 0.1\)
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Implement Robust controller:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Nominal PID + robust compensator with disturbance bound \(\rho = 1.5\) N
  \end{itemize}
\item
  Run hover test at \([0, 0, 1]\) for 30 seconds with wind, record all three controllers.
\item
  Compare:

  \begin{itemize}
  \tightlist
  \item
    Maximum position deviation from setpoint
  \item
    Steady-state offset (PID will have nonzero offset without integral wind-up compensation)
  \item
    Control effort (motor speed variance)
  \end{itemize}
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Expected Results:} SMC should achieve the smallest steady-state drift (\textasciitilde4 cm) due to its inherent disturbance rejection on the sliding surface. Robust control should be next (\textasciitilde5 cm). PID will show the largest drift (\textasciitilde15 cm) unless the integral gain is significantly increased, which risks oscillation.

\hypertarget{quick-quiz-quadrotor-control-in-ros2}{%
\paragraph{Quick Quiz: Quadrotor Control in ROS2}\label{quick-quiz-quadrotor-control-in-ros2}}

\textbf{Q1.} In a cascaded control architecture, why must the inner rate loop run at a higher frequency (e.g., 500 Hz) than the outer position loop (e.g., 50 Hz)?

\hypertarget{answer}{%
\paragraph{Answer}\label{answer}}

The inner loop must be fast enough that it appears as an instantaneous actuator to the outer loop. The rule of thumb is that each inner loop should be 5--10x faster than the loop that commands it. If the rate loop were too slow, the attitude loop would command rate changes that take too long to execute, leading to phase lag and potential instability in the outer loop. Additionally, the angular rate dynamics are the fastest dynamics in the quadrotor system (small inertia, high torques), so the rate controller must sample at or above the Nyquist rate of these dynamics.

\textbf{Q2.} The motor mixing matrix \(M\) has dimensions \(4 \times 4\). Under what condition is \(M\) invertible? What physical situation would make it singular?

\hypertarget{answer-1}{%
\paragraph{Answer}\label{answer-1}}

\(M\) is invertible when the four motors can independently produce the four wrench components (thrust, roll torque, pitch torque, yaw torque). It becomes singular if, for example, all motors are collocated (arm length \(d = 0\)), which makes the roll and pitch torque rows identical to zero. It would also be singular if the yaw torque coefficients were all equal (no counter-rotating pairs), as you could not produce differential yaw torque. In the standard plus or X configuration with properly counter-rotating motors, \(M\) is always full rank.

\textbf{Q3.} Why is MPC typically placed in the outer position loop (10--20 Hz) rather than the inner rate loop for a quadrotor?

\hypertarget{answer-2}{%
\paragraph{Answer}\label{answer-2}}

MPC involves solving a constrained quadratic program at each cycle, which takes 1--50 ms depending on the horizon length and solver. This computation time is acceptable at 10--20 Hz (50--100 ms period) but would miss deadlines at 500 Hz (2 ms period). The position dynamics are the slowest, so the prediction horizon can be longer without excessive computation. The inner rate loop uses simpler controllers (PID, LQR) that execute in microseconds, ensuring the tight timing needed for angular rate stabilization.

\textbf{Q4.} In the complementary filter \(\hat{\phi}_{k+1} = \alpha(\hat{\phi}_k + \omega_x \Delta t) + (1-\alpha)\phi_\text{acc}\), what happens if \(\alpha = 1.0\)? What if \(\alpha = 0.0\)?

\hypertarget{answer-3}{%
\paragraph{Answer}\label{answer-3}}

If \(\alpha = 1.0\), the filter becomes pure gyroscope integration: \(\hat{\phi}_{k+1} = \hat{\phi}_k + \omega_x \Delta t\). This will drift over time due to gyro bias, eventually producing arbitrarily large errors. If \(\alpha = 0.0\), the filter uses only the accelerometer: \(\hat{\phi}_{k+1} = \phi_\text{acc}\). This eliminates drift but produces a very noisy estimate and is invalid during translational acceleration (the accelerometer measures gravity plus linear acceleration, so the gravity-derived angle is wrong during maneuvers). Typical values of \(\alpha = 0.95\)--\(0.99\) balance gyro responsiveness with accelerometer stability.

\textbf{Q5.} Which of the seven controllers would you recommend for a delivery drone that must pick up packages of unknown weight? Justify your choice.

\hypertarget{answer-4}{%
\paragraph{Answer}\label{answer-4}}

\textbf{Adaptive Control} is the best choice. When the drone picks up a package, its mass \(m\) and inertia \(J\) change suddenly. Adaptive control uses online parameter estimation to update \(\hat{m}\) and \(\hat{J}\) in real-time, adjusting the control law accordingly. The regressor-based formulation \(\tau = Y(q, \dot{q}, \dot{q}_r, \ddot{q}_r)\hat{\theta}\) can track mass changes within a few seconds. PID would work but would require aggressive integral action and retuning. LQR and MPC would degrade because the linearized model is incorrect for the new mass. Computed Torque would produce incorrect compensation torques until the model is updated. A practical hybrid approach combines Adaptive control with MPC: the adaptive law estimates parameters, and MPC uses the updated model for trajectory optimization.

\hypertarget{summary}{%
\subsection{Summary}\label{summary}}

\hypertarget{key-takeaways}{%
\subsubsection{Key Takeaways}\label{key-takeaways}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{Cascaded Architecture is Standard:} The three-loop cascade (position → attitude → rate) is used by every major flight controller (PX4, ArduPilot, DJI, BetaFlight). Each loop runs at a different frequency, with inner loops 5--10x faster than outer loops. In ROS2, this maps naturally to separate nodes communicating via topics.
\item
  \textbf{Motor Mixing Matrix is the Bridge:} The \(4 \times 4\) mixing matrix \(M\) converts desired thrust and torques into individual motor speed commands. Its inverse \(M^{-1}\) is precomputed and applied at every control cycle. Getting this matrix correct is the first step toward any quadrotor controller.
\item
  \textbf{Complementary Filter Enables Attitude Estimation:} Fusing gyroscope and accelerometer data with a tunable parameter \(\alpha\) provides a computationally cheap attitude estimate suitable for inner-loop control. Production systems use Mahony or extended Kalman filters.
\item
  \textbf{No Single Controller Wins Everything:} PID is simple and robust to tune. LQR is energy-optimal near hover. MPC handles constraints and trajectory preview. SMC and Robust control excel at wind rejection. Adaptive control handles changing payloads. Backstepping provides formal stability guarantees. CTC gives exact linearization when the model is accurate.
\item
  \textbf{ROS2 Enables Modular Controller Swapping:} Because each controller is a separate ROS2 node with standardized topic interfaces (\texttt{/attitude\_cmd} in, \texttt{/motor\_cmd} out), you can swap controllers without modifying the rest of the system. This is the power of the ROS2 architecture for rapid prototyping and comparison.
\item
  \textbf{Real-Time Matters:} The inner rate loop must execute within 1--2 ms. PID and LQR easily meet this. MPC requires careful solver selection and runs in the outer loop. Use timer-based callbacks, pre-allocate memory, and avoid heap allocation in control loops.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{preparation-for-week-11}{%
\subsubsection{Preparation for Week 11}\label{preparation-for-week-11}}

Next week we move to \textbf{Multi-Robot Coordination and Formation Control}. We will extend the single-quadrotor controllers from this week to multi-agent systems, implementing consensus-based formation control, leader-follower architectures, and collision avoidance using ROS2 multi-node communication patterns. Complete all three activities from this week before the next session.

\hypertarget{running-the-ros2-demo}{%
\subsection{Running the ROS2 Demo}\label{running-the-ros2-demo}}

\hypertarget{build-and-source}{%
\subsubsection{Build and Source}\label{build-and-source}}

cd \textasciitilde/auto\_control\_ws
colcon build -\/-packages-select week\_06\_quadrotor\_dynamics
source install/setup.bash

\hypertarget{launch-the-demo}{%
\subsubsection{Launch the Demo}\label{launch-the-demo}}

ros2 launch week\_06\_quadrotor\_dynamics demo.launch.py

This command replays the recorded bag data at 2x speed, starts three solution nodes (attitude estimation, PID control, motor mixing), and opens RViz2 with a preconfigured layout.

\hypertarget{ros2-topics}{%
\subsubsection{ROS2 Topics}\label{ros2-topics}}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}llll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Topic & Type & Source & Description \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
\texttt{/imu} & sensor\_msgs/Imu & Bag & Raw IMU data at 1000 Hz \\
\texttt{/desired\_attitude} & geometry\_msgs/QuaternionStamped & Bag & Attitude setpoints at 100 Hz \\
\texttt{/motor\_commands} & std\_msgs/Float32MultiArray & Bag & Motor speed telemetry at 100 Hz \\
\texttt{/ground\_truth\_pose} & geometry\_msgs/PoseStamped & Bag & Ground truth from motion capture at 100 Hz \\
\end{longtable}

\hypertarget{expected-rviz2-output}{%
\subsubsection{Expected RViz2 Output}\label{expected-rviz2-output}}

RViz2 will display the quadrotor\textquotesingle s estimated attitude (from the complementary filter) alongside the ground truth pose. You should see the attitude estimate converging to ground truth within the first few seconds. Motor command markers will show thrust allocation across the four rotors.

\hypertarget{troubleshooting}{%
\subsubsection{Troubleshooting}\label{troubleshooting}}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{RViz2 crashes on launch:} The launch file filters \texttt{snap} paths from \texttt{LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH} automatically. If RViz2 still crashes, try: \texttt{export\ LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH=\$(echo\ \$LD\_LIBRARY\_PATH\ \textbar{}\ tr\ \textquotesingle{}:\textquotesingle{}\ \textquotesingle{}\textbackslash{}n\textquotesingle{}\ \textbar{}\ grep\ -v\ snap\ \textbar{}\ tr\ \textquotesingle{}\textbackslash{}n\textquotesingle{}\ \textquotesingle{}:\textquotesingle{})}
\item
  \textbf{No data visible:} Ensure the bag file exists at \texttt{w06\_exercises/bag\_data/synthetic\_quadrotor/}. Re-run \texttt{colcon\ build} if needed.
\item
  \textbf{QoS mismatch warnings:} The bag uses default QoS. If your subscriber uses \texttt{BEST\_EFFORT}, switch to \texttt{RELIABLE} or use \texttt{-\/-qos-profile-overrides-path}.
\end{itemize}

\hypertarget{appendix-review-material-ros2-control-implementation}{%
\subsection{Appendix: Review Material --- ROS2 Control Implementation}\label{appendix-review-material-ros2-control-implementation}}

\hypertarget{question-1-25-marks}{%
\paragraph{Question 1 (25 marks)}\label{question-1-25-marks}}

Explain the architecture of a ROS2 control node for a robotic system. In your answer:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  Identify the topics a typical ROS2 control node subscribes to (sensor feedback) and publishes (actuator commands). \emph{(5 marks)}
\item
  Explain how the control loop rate is managed using \texttt{create\_timer()} and why deterministic timing is important for controller stability. \emph{(8 marks)}
\item
  Compare \textbf{timer-based} control loops (fixed-rate callbacks) versus \textbf{event-driven} control loops (triggered on new sensor data). Discuss the advantages and disadvantages of each approach in terms of latency, jitter, and computational load. \emph{(12 marks)}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{model-answer-q1}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer --- Q1}\label{model-answer-q1}}

\textbf{Part (a):} A typical ROS2 control node subscribes to state-feedback topics such as \texttt{/odom} (nav\_msgs/Odometry) for position and velocity, \texttt{/imu} (sensor\_msgs/Imu) for angular velocity and linear acceleration, and \texttt{/joint\_states} (sensor\_msgs/JointState) for joint-level feedback. It publishes actuator commands on topics like \texttt{/cmd\_vel} (geometry\_msgs/Twist), \texttt{/motor\_cmd} (std\_msgs/Float64MultiArray), or \texttt{/joint\_commands}.

\textbf{Part (b):} The control loop rate is managed by calling \texttt{self.create\_timer(period\_sec,\ callback)} in the node constructor. For example, \texttt{self.create\_timer(0.01,\ self.control\_callback)} creates a 100 Hz control loop. Deterministic timing is critical because the discrete-time controller gains (Kp, Ki, Kd) are tuned for a specific sample period \(\Delta t\). Jitter in the control period effectively changes the derivative and integral computations, potentially causing instability. The integral term accumulates error multiplied by \(\Delta t\): if \(\Delta t\) varies unpredictably, the integral grows incorrectly. For derivative action, \(u_d = K_d \cdot (e_k - e_{k-1})/\Delta t\), inconsistent \(\Delta t\) amplifies noise.

\textbf{Part (c):}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Aspect & Timer-Based (Fixed-Rate) & Event-Driven (Sensor-Triggered) \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
Timing & Fixed period (e.g., 100 Hz), decoupled from sensor rate & Fires when new sensor message arrives \\
Latency & Average latency = half the control period; worst case = full period & Minimal latency --- processes data immediately upon arrival \\
Jitter & Low jitter if OS scheduling is adequate; consistent \(\Delta t\) & Jitter depends on sensor timing; inconsistent \(\Delta t\) \\
Computational load & Predictable, evenly spaced CPU usage & Bursty --- may overload if multiple sensors arrive simultaneously \\
Best for & Inner-loop controllers needing guaranteed rate (PID, LQR) & High-level planners, vision-based control where data is sparse \\
\end{longtable}

In practice, most flight controllers (PX4, ArduPilot) use timer-based loops for attitude and rate control, with event-driven callbacks only for updating the latest sensor data into shared buffers that the timer callback reads.

\hypertarget{question-2-25-marks}{%
\paragraph{Question 2 (25 marks)}\label{question-2-25-marks}}

You implemented PID, LQR, and MPC as separate ROS2 control nodes in Week 9. Compare their computational requirements per control cycle by answering the following:

\begin{enumerate}
\tightlist
\item
  List the main mathematical operations each controller performs per cycle (e.g., matrix multiply, quadratic program solve). \emph{(9 marks)}
\item
  Estimate the approximate floating-point operation (FLOP) count per cycle for a system with \(n = 12\) states and \(m = 4\) inputs. \emph{(8 marks)}
\item
  Which of the three controllers requires hard real-time guarantees and why? What ROS2 mechanisms (executor type, QoS settings) help achieve this? \emph{(8 marks)}
\end{enumerate}

\hypertarget{model-answer-q2}{%
\paragraph{Model Answer --- Q2}\label{model-answer-q2}}

\textbf{Part (a):}

\begin{itemize}
\tightlist
\item
  \textbf{PID:} Per axis: 1 subtraction (error), 1 multiply + 1 add (P term), 1 multiply + 1 add (I accumulation), 1 subtraction + 1 division (D term), 1 addition (sum). For 4 axes: \textasciitilde40 FLOPs total. Constant time O(1).
\item
  \textbf{LQR:} One matrix-vector multiplication \(\mathbf{u} = -K(\mathbf{x} - \mathbf{x}_d)\) where \(K \in \mathbb{R}^{4 \times 12}\). This is \(4 \times 12 = 48\) multiplies and \(4 \times 11 = 44\) additions, plus 12 subtractions for the error vector. Total: \textasciitilde104 FLOPs. Also O(1) since K is precomputed.
\item
  \textbf{MPC:} At each cycle, solves a constrained quadratic program (QP). For a horizon \(N = 20\) with 12 states and 4 inputs, the QP has \(20 \times 4 = 80\) decision variables and \(20 \times (12 + 4 \times 2) = 400\) constraints. An interior-point solver typically requires 10--30 iterations, each involving a \(80 \times 80\) matrix factorization. Approximate cost: \(O(N^3 m^3)\) per solve, roughly \(10^4\)--\(10^6\) FLOPs.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Part (b):}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule\noalign{}
Controller & FLOPs / Cycle & Typical Time on ARM Cortex \\
\midrule\noalign{}
\endhead
\bottomrule\noalign{}
\endlastfoot
PID & \textasciitilde40 & \textless{} 1 μs \\
LQR & \textasciitilde104 & \textasciitilde2 μs \\
MPC (N=20) & \textasciitilde10\textsuperscript{5} & 1--50 ms \\
\end{longtable}

\textbf{Part (c):} PID and LQR both require hard real-time guarantees because they run in the inner attitude/rate loop at 250--1000 Hz. Missing a deadline causes immediate instability in an airborne vehicle. MPC typically runs at 10--50 Hz in the outer position loop and can tolerate slight deadline misses (the previous solution is applied if the new one is late). In ROS2, real-time is supported by: (1) using a \textbf{SingleThreadedExecutor} on a dedicated thread with SCHED\_FIFO priority, (2) setting QoS to \texttt{BEST\_EFFORT} reliability with small queue depths to avoid blocking, (3) pre-allocating all memory to avoid heap allocation in the control loop, and (4) using the \texttt{rclcpp} real-time-safe utilities or the \texttt{realtime\_tools} package.

